column1: # sent_id = 1888_Doerr_Goederschlaechter_p2_11

# text_orig = Dat Röberpack hett hier Anno Söss to gottlos hus't, wat ik as Jung betügen kann, denn mi hett dunmals en Schafför en Ohrfieg staken, as se mi min Lewdag nich wedder an den Kopp flagen is.
# remark = "to gottlos" is likely a structural borrowing from Standard German ("zu gottlos"). This is characteristic for 19th c. written Low German.
# variety = East Low German, North Markian (Nordmärkisch), Uckermark
# sent_id = 1884_Hill_Eekbom_Krienke_p111_4
# text_orig = Fritz un Gottfried weern twungen, still to hollen un müßten Tokiker sin von de Ding', de da vör sik gahn sullen.
# remark = Influenced by Fritz Reuter, Hill writes /a/ instead of conventional å (oa)
# variety = East Low German, Central Pomeranian (Mittelpommersch), Uckermark
# sent_id = 1901_Post_Falks_Krienke_p122_2

# text_orig = Dag's un nachts was se immer prat, ehr Schützling', so as de Kluck ehr Küken, vör Undœg' to bewohren, un dat müsst ehr de Neid laten, dat se met ehr Husmiddel gegen Kinnerkrankheiten al anner Frugens in'n Urt den Dum upt Og' drücken ded'.
# remark = “dag’s un nachts” could be influenced by standard German, a modern equivalent would be “Dach un Nacht” (no case)
# variety = East Low German, North Markian (Nordmärkisch), Uckermark
# sent_id = 1930_Sydow_Koester_Krienke_p208_10
# text_orig = He was as 'n armen Jungen nah Berlin kamen und hadd sich dörch Singen in 'd Domchor un nohstens an de Oper verdeenen müßt, um so väl to hebben, dat he stodeeren lehren künn.
# remark = “um” is possibly a typo for Low German üm, “und” is certainly one for “un”
# variety = East Low German, Central Pomeranian (Mittelpommersch), Uckermark
# sent_id = 1843_Arndt_Maehrchen_p6_2

# text_orig = De olde Löwe was dood, un eenen Löwen wullen se nich wedder; denn se seden: De hett scharpe Tänen un eenen Buk as een Oss un frett in Eenem furt, un man schall et sich noch as eene Gnad reknen, wenn he Eenen tom Hawe röppt, datt man in sinen majestätschen Buk herunnerspazieren mütt.

# remark = Among Western Pomeranian, the language of the island of Rügen is atypical in not diphthongizing ê and ô; Arndt’s text shows partial preservation of dative, this is untypical for the modern dialect and could be either standard German influence or an archaism. Note that this is among the oldest attested modern Low German texts from the region. In any case, he also uses more morphologically accusative forms for suspected datives.
# variety = East Low German, Western Pomeranian (Vorpommersch), Rügen
# sent_id = 1854_Firmenich_Pudmin_p87_1

# text_orig = To Pudmin bi Swantow up Roien waant vördissen ene olle Buursfru, de harr soewen Kinner, lutter Dierns, een ümmer 'n bēten lǖtter as de anner; eer Mooder heel se smuck in Kleding, un truck se ümmer oewereens an; se harren all bunte Jopen, bunte Schörten, un rode Hüllen up.
# variety = East Low German, Western Pomeranian (Vorpommersch), Rügen
# sent_id = 1868_Englien_Schpizbuowen_p155_3

# text_orig = Ees woar deär Jonge met sine Schoape dicht annen Busch, doa kam in Jäer ruet, deär hadde inne Flinte un inne Vijjeline un wulle met eäm tueschen; heä sulle eäm diä 5 Schoape jeäwen, doaveär sul er diä Flinte un diä Vijjeline hebben.
# variety = East Low German, Central Markian (Mittelmärkisch), Neumark
# sent_id = 1854_Firmenich3_Hohenwalde_p118_8
# text_orig = Na Bröderkin, nu sie mi ook willkoam vom Duum bes an 'n Ellboan, un bes an't holle Lief.
# variety = East Low German, Central Markian (Mittelmärkisch), Neumark
